      "side": 1,
      "message": "Incorrect Variable Comparison - Variable in Quotes\n```\n# Current code (test_policies_sub_menu.robot:422)\nIF  \u0027$initial_option_value\u0027 \u003d\u003d \u0027Enabled\u0027\n\n```\n# Previous code (patchset 2, line 396)\n\n```\nIF  \u0027${initial_option_value}\u0027 \u003d\u003d \u0027Enabled\u0027\n```\nFix Required:\n```\nIF  ${initial_option_value} \u003d\u003d \u0027Enabled\u0027\n```\n\nWhy: BOTH versions are incorrect. When a variable is enclosed in quotes in Robot Framework, it\u0027s treated as a literal string, not a variable reference. Both \u0027${initial_option_value}\u0027 and \u0027$initial_option_value\u0027 compare the LITERAL STRING against \u0027Enabled\u0027, not the variable\u0027s value. The variable must be outside the quotes to be evaluated. This bug exists in both patchset 2 and 3, but patchset 3\u0027s change makes it more obvious. The test likely never worked correctly.",
      "revId": "654fe80928dad77121c97f132567baa04a2886ec",
      "serverId": "adbd0a64-1f21-4d83-b585-671fe73cb6e4"
